etymologies: early 19th century; earliest use found in Samuel Singer (1783–1858), literary scholar. From over- + speed

definitions: Excessive speed; especially the operation of an engine, vehicle, etc., at a speed higher than is safe or appropriate; an instance of this.

etymologies: late 17th century; earliest use found in John Evelyn (1620–1706), diarist and writer. From over- + speed

definitions: To travel too quickly, especially to travel faster than permitted by law or by another authority. Also with object: to cause (a vehicle) to travel more quickly than is safe. Now chiefly in African and South Asian use.
To operate (an engine or other machine) at a speed higher than is safe for its gearing or other components.
